MOTION TO MODIFY CUSTODY ORDER

     NOW COMES Plaintiff/Father, Andrew J. Pigors, and respectfully moves this Court pursuant to MCL 722.27 and MCR 3.211 for an Order modifying the custody provisions of the July 17, 2024 Judgment of Divorce and Order Regarding Custody and Parenting Time, to establish joint physical custody with equal parenting time, or in the alternative, to establish Father as the primary physical custodian. In support thereof, Plaintiff states as follows:

I. RELIEF REQUESTED

     Plaintiff respectfully requests that this Court:

     A. Find that proper cause exists and/or there has been a change of circumstances warranting modification of custody;

     B. Find that an established custodial environment exists with both parents, or alternatively, only with Defendant;

     C. Conduct a best interests analysis under MCL 722.23;

     D. Modify the current custody order to establish joint physical custody with equal parenting time (182.5 overnights per year each); or in the alternative,

     E. Establish Plaintiff as the primary physical custodian with Defendant receiving reasonable parenting time;

     F. Order makeup parenting time for the 329+ days of wrongful deprivation;

     G. Order Defendant to comply with MCL 722.27a and facilitate parenting time;

     H. Award attorney fees and costs to Plaintiff pursuant to MCR 3.206(C); and

     I. Grant such other and further relief as this Court deems just and equitable.

II. JURISDICTION AND PROCEDURAL HISTORY

     1. This Court has continuing jurisdiction over this matter pursuant to MCL 722.27.

     2. On July 17, 2024, this Court entered an Order Regarding Custody and Parenting Time, establishing the following:
          • Joint legal custody to both parents
          • Primary physical custody to Defendant/Mother
          • Parenting time to Plaintiff/Father: 79 overnights per year

     3. Prior to the July 17, 2024 order, Plaintiff and Defendant had maintained an informal shared parenting arrangement with Plaintiff exercising approximately 182.5 overnights per year (50% parenting time).

     4. The July 17, 2024 order represented a 56.7% reduction in Plaintiff's parenting time, from 182.5 overnights to 79 overnights per year, a loss of 103.5 overnights annually.

     5. Following the July 17, 2024 order, Defendant has systematically interfered with and prevented Plaintiff's court-ordered parenting time through:
          a. False allegations of threat, poisoning, assault, and child safety concerns;
          b. Procurement of a Personal Protection Order (Case No. 2023-5907-PP) based on false allegations;
          c. Unilateral withholding of the child from Plaintiff;
          d. Filing repeated emergency motions seeking ex parte suspension of parenting time.

     6. Between March 28, 2024 and the present date (February 11, 2026), Defendant has deprived Plaintiff of 329+ days of parenting time, including:
          • March 28 - May 5, 2024: 39 days
          • October 20 - November 15, 2024: 26 days
          • Various other periods: 72 days
          • August 8, 2025 - February 11, 2026: 192+ days (ongoing ex parte suspension)

     7. A comprehensive HealthWest psychological evaluation was completed in 2024, which:
          • Found no mental health issues, instability, or safety concerns with Plaintiff;
          • Documented Defendant's pattern of gatekeeping and interference;
          • Documented systematic parental alienation by Defendant;
          • Recommended restoration and expansion of parenting time to Plaintiff.

     8. All of Defendant's allegations of threat, poisoning, assault, mental instability, and child endangerment have been conclusively disproven by:
          • Medical records (no poisoning, no injuries);
          • Police investigation reports (no criminal basis found);
          • HealthWest evaluation (no mental health concerns);
          • Court records (equal legal custody awarded on July 17, 2024, contradicting threat allegations).

III. LEGAL STANDARD

A. Established Custodial Environment

     Under MCL 722.27(1)(c), the Court must first determine whether an established custodial environment exists with one or both parents. An established custodial environment exists if:

     "The child naturally looks to the custodian in that environment for guidance, discipline, the necessities of life, and parental comfort." Foskett v Foskett, 247 Mich App 1, 7; 634 NW2d 363 (2001).

     The focus is on the child's perspective and the parent-child relationship, not merely the passage of time. Baker v Baker, 411 Mich 567, 579; 309 NW2d 532 (1981).

B. Proper Cause or Change of Circumstances

     To modify a custody order, the moving party must demonstrate either proper cause or a change of circumstances by clear and convincing evidence. MCL 722.27(1)(c); Vodvarka v Grasmeyer, 259 Mich App 499, 511; 675 NW2d 847 (2003).

     "Proper cause" means one or more appropriate grounds that have or could have a significant effect on the child's life to the extent that a reevaluation of the child's custodial situation should be undertaken. Shade v Wright, 291 Mich App 17, 21; 805 NW2d 1 (2010).

     "Change of circumstances" refers to circumstances that have changed since the entry of the last custody order and that have or could have a significant effect on the child requiring a reevaluation of custody. Id.

     Relevant factors in determining proper cause or change of circumstances include:
     • Violations of custody or parenting time orders
     • Parental gatekeeping and interference
     • Material changes in the parties' circumstances
     • Changes in the child's developmental needs
     • Evidence of parental alienation

C. Best Interests Standard

     Once proper cause or change of circumstances is established, the Court must evaluate custody using the twelve best interest factors enumerated in MCL 722.23:

     (a) The love, affection, and other emotional ties existing between the parties involved and the child;

     (b) The capacity and disposition of the parties involved to give the child love, affection, and guidance and to continue the education and raising of the child in his or her religion or creed, if any;

     (c) The capacity and disposition of the parties involved to provide the child with food, clothing, medical care or other remedial care recognized and permitted under the laws of this state in place of medical care, and other material needs;

     (d) The length of time the child has lived in a stable, satisfactory environment, and the desirability of maintaining continuity;

     (e) The permanence, as a family unit, of the existing or proposed custodial home or homes;

     (f) The moral fitness of the parties involved;

     (g) The mental and physical health of the parties involved;

     (h) The home, school, and community record of the child;

     (i) The reasonable preference of the child, if the court considers the child to be of sufficient age to express preference;

     (j) The willingness and ability of each of the parties to facilitate and encourage a close and continuing parent-child relationship between the child and the other parent or the child and the parents;

     (k) Domestic violence, regardless of whether the violence was directed against or witnessed by the child;

     (l) Any other factor considered by the court to be relevant to a particular child custody dispute.

D. Burden of Proof

     Where an established custodial environment exists, the moving party must prove by clear and convincing evidence that the proposed change is in the child's best interests. MCL 722.27(1)(c); Berger v Berger, 277 Mich App 700, 705; 747 NW2d 336 (2008).

     Where no established custodial environment exists, or where an established custodial environment exists with both parents, the moving party must prove by a preponderance of the evidence that the proposed change is in the child's best interests. Id.

IV. ARGUMENT

A. ESTABLISHED CUSTODIAL ENVIRONMENT EXISTS WITH BOTH PARENTS

     1. An established custodial environment exists with Plaintiff/Father.

     Prior to court involvement, Plaintiff maintained approximately 50% parenting time (182.5 overnights per year) with the child. During this time:

          • Plaintiff provided daily care, including feeding, bathing, clothing, and transportation;
          • Plaintiff attended to the child's medical needs and appointments;
          • Plaintiff participated in the child's education and developmental activities;
          • Plaintiff maintained a stable home environment;
          • The child naturally looked to Plaintiff for guidance, discipline, necessities, and parental comfort.

     This parent-child bond was recognized by this Court in the July 17, 2024 order awarding equal legal custody to both parents, acknowledging Plaintiff's role as a co-parent.

     The HealthWest evaluation documents Plaintiff's appropriate parenting capacity, strong bond with the child, and ability to meet the child's needs.

     2. An established custodial environment exists with Defendant/Mother.

     The child has resided primarily with Defendant since the July 17, 2024 order and naturally looks to Defendant for guidance, discipline, necessities, and parental comfort.

     3. Alternatively, if the Court finds an established custodial environment exists only with Defendant, Plaintiff can meet the clear and convincing evidence standard based on the egregious circumstances detailed herein.

B. PROPER CAUSE EXISTS

     Proper cause exists to modify custody based on the following grounds:

     1. Systematic Violation of Court-Ordered Parenting Time (329+ Days Deprivation)

     Defendant has willfully and systematically violated court-ordered parenting time, depriving Plaintiff of 329+ days of contact with his child since March 2024. This includes:

          • 39 days of unilateral withholding (March 28 - May 5, 2024)
          • 26 days of withholding (October 20 - November 15, 2024)
          • 192+ days under ex parte suspension orders obtained through false allegations (August 8, 2025 - present)
          • Additional periods totaling 72 days

     Michigan law recognizes that interference with parenting time constitutes proper cause for custody modification. Friend v Friend, 407 Mich 968 (1979); MacIntyre v MacIntyre, 267 Mich App 449 (2005).

     The systematic nature of these violations—spanning nearly two years and involving 329+ days of deprivation—demonstrates a pattern of willful gatekeeping that has profoundly disrupted the parent-child relationship and warrants immediate reevaluation of custody.

     2. Pattern of False Allegations and Parental Alienation

     Defendant has engaged in a systematic campaign of false allegations designed to eliminate Plaintiff from the child's life, including:

          • False allegations of suicidality (2 incidents, Oct 2023 & June 2024) - disproven by medical records
          • False allegations of poisoning - disproven by medical records and police investigation
          • False allegations of assault - disproven by police investigation
          • False allegations of mental instability - disproven by HealthWest evaluation
          • False allegations of threat - contradicted by Court's own order awarding equal legal custody on July 17, 2024

     The HealthWest evaluation specifically documents:
          • Defendant's pattern of gatekeeping
          • Systematic parental alienation
          • Absence of any legitimate safety concerns regarding Plaintiff
          • Recommendation for restoration and expansion of Plaintiff's parenting time

     This pattern of fabricated allegations constitutes:
          • Fraud on the court (MCR 2.612)
          • Contempt of court (violation of MCL 722.27a duty to facilitate parenting time)
          • Proper cause for custody modification based on moral fitness concerns (MCL 722.23(f))
          • Evidence of unwillingness to facilitate relationship (MCL 722.23(j))

     3. Procurement of Fraudulent Personal Protection Order

     On November 17, 2023, Defendant obtained a Personal Protection Order (Case No. 2023-5907-PP) based on demonstrably false allegations of threat and danger. The allegations underlying this PPO have been conclusively disproven by:

          • Police investigation finding no credible basis
          • Medical records contradicting poisoning claims
          • HealthWest evaluation finding no mental health or safety concerns
          • This Court's own July 17, 2024 order awarding equal legal custody (which would be unconscionable if Defendant's threat allegations were true)

     The fraudulent PPO has been used as a weapon to:
          • Interfere with Plaintiff's parenting time
          • Justify repeated ex parte suspension orders
          • Damage Plaintiff's reputation and relationship with the child
          • Circumvent normal custody procedures

     Use of fraudulent restraining orders to manipulate custody outcomes constitutes proper cause for modification. See Dailey v Kloenhamer, 291 Mich App 660 (2011).

     4. Material Change in Parties' Circumstances

     Since the July 17, 2024 order:

          • Plaintiff has completed the HealthWest evaluation, which found him to be an appropriate caregiver with no mental health or safety concerns
          • Defendant's false allegations have been systematically disproven
          • Defendant's pattern of gatekeeping and alienation has been professionally documented
          • The parent-child relationship between Plaintiff and the child has been severely damaged by 329+ days of deprivation
          • The child's need for a relationship with both parents has increased as Defendant's interference has intensified

     These changes have a significant effect on the child's life and require a reevaluation of custody.

C. CHANGE OF CIRCUMSTANCES EXISTS

     Alternatively, or in addition to proper cause, a change of circumstances exists warranting modification:

     1. 329+ Days of Wrongful Parenting Time Deprivation

     The most significant change since the July 17, 2024 order is the complete deprivation of Plaintiff's relationship with his child. What was ordered as 79 overnights per year has become zero overnights since August 8, 2025—a period now exceeding 192 days.

     This is not merely a violation of the parenting time schedule; it is a complete elimination of the parent-child relationship, achieved through:
          • False allegations
          • Abuse of ex parte procedures
          • Strategic use of a fraudulent PPO
          • Systematic gatekeeping

     The impact on the child is profound and constitutes a changed circumstance requiring immediate intervention.

     2. Professional Documentation of Parental Alienation

     The HealthWest evaluation provides professional confirmation of:
          • Defendant's gatekeeping behaviors
          • Systematic alienation tactics
          • Absence of legitimate safety concerns
          • Harm to the child from deprivation of the father-child relationship

     This professional assessment represents new evidence that was not available at the time of the July 17, 2024 order and constitutes a material change warranting reevaluation.

     3. Escalating Pattern of False Allegations

     Since the July 17, 2024 order, Defendant's false allegations have escalated in frequency and severity:

          • August 2025: New emergency motions filed
          • September 2025: Continued ex parte suspensions
          • October 2025: Continued ex parte suspensions
          • November 2025: Continued ex parte suspensions
          • December 2025: Pattern continues
          • January 2026: Pattern continues
          • February 2026: No restoration of parenting time

     Each continuation represents a new false representation to the Court that an emergency exists requiring suspension of parenting time, when in fact:
          • No police investigation has been initiated
          • No criminal charges have been filed
          • No CPS findings have been made
          • All prior allegations have been disproven
          • The HealthWest evaluation found no concerns

     This escalating pattern represents a material change from the circumstances existing at the time of the July 17, 2024 order.

     4. Defendant's Demonstrated Unwillingness to Facilitate Relationship

     MCL 722.23(j) requires evaluation of "the willingness and ability of each of the parties to facilitate and encourage a close and continuing parent-child relationship between the child and the other parent."

     Since the July 17, 2024 order, Defendant has demonstrated not merely an unwillingness, but an active campaign to eliminate the parent-child relationship through:
          • 329+ days of deprivation
          • False allegations designed to justify elimination of parenting time
          • Abuse of emergency procedures
          • Violation of MCL 722.27a's presumption favoring parenting time
          • Documented alienation behaviors

     This is not the circumstance that existed at the time of the July 17, 2024 trial. The Court could not have known at that time that Defendant would engage in such systematic elimination of Plaintiff's relationship with the child. This represents a profound change of circumstances.

D. BEST INTERESTS ANALYSIS FAVORS MODIFICATION

     Applying the twelve statutory best interest factors under MCL 722.23, the evidence overwhelmingly favors modification of custody to establish either joint physical custody or Plaintiff as primary physical custodian.

1. Factor (a): Love, Affection, and Emotional Ties

     FAVORS PLAINTIFF (or EQUAL)

     Plaintiff has maintained a strong, loving relationship with the child since birth. Prior to court involvement, Plaintiff exercised 50% parenting time and served as a primary caregiver. The HealthWest evaluation documents Plaintiff's appropriate emotional bond with the child.

     Defendant has systematically attempted to sever the emotional bond between Plaintiff and the child through alienation tactics and deprivation. The 329+ days of wrongful deprivation have damaged but not destroyed this bond.

     The child's need for both parents' love and affection supports restoration of Plaintiff's parenting time.

2. Factor (b): Capacity to Provide Love, Affection, and Guidance

     FAVORS PLAINTIFF

     Plaintiff has demonstrated capacity and disposition to provide love, affection, and guidance throughout the child's life. The HealthWest evaluation confirms Plaintiff's appropriate parenting capacity.

     Defendant's capacity is called into question by:
          • Pattern of false allegations (demonstrating poor judgment)
          • Willingness to use the child as a weapon against Plaintiff
          • Documented alienation behaviors (prioritizing her conflict with Plaintiff over the child's need for both parents)
          • Violation of MCL 722.27a (demonstrating unwillingness to follow court orders)

3. Factor (c): Capacity to Provide Material Needs

     EQUAL or FAVORS PLAINTIFF

     Both parties have demonstrated capacity to provide food, clothing, medical care, and material needs.

     Plaintiff maintains stable employment and housing appropriate for the child. Plaintiff has consistently provided financial support.

4. Factor (d): Stable Environment and Continuity

     FAVORS DEFENDANT (or EQUAL with modification)

     Defendant has provided the primary residence since July 17, 2024. However:

          • Prior to July 2024, the child maintained stability in both homes under the 50/50 arrangement
          • The current "stability" has been achieved through unlawful deprivation of the child's relationship with Plaintiff
          • Stability achieved through wrongful means should not be rewarded
          • The child's need for stability includes stability of relationship with both parents
          • Restoration of meaningful parenting time with Plaintiff will restore the continuity of that relationship

     Courts must balance physical stability against relational stability. A child who has been wrongfully deprived of a parent for 329+ days has not experienced true stability, but rather trauma.

5. Factor (e): Permanence as Family Unit

     EQUAL

     Both parties can provide permanence as a family unit. Plaintiff maintains a stable home and employment. Defendant maintains a stable home.

     The key question is whether the family unit includes both parents or only one. MCL 722.27a presumes that the child's family unit should include both parents absent clear and convincing evidence to the contrary.

6. Factor (f): Moral Fitness

     STRONGLY FAVORS PLAINTIFF

     This factor weighs heavily in Plaintiff's favor:

     PLAINTIFF:
          • No criminal record
          • No history of dishonesty or fraud
          • Complied with court orders
          • Acted in accordance with law and court procedures
          • All allegations against him disproven
          • HealthWest evaluation found no concerns

     DEFENDANT:
          • Systematically made false allegations to law enforcement and courts
          • Obtained fraudulent PPO through misrepresentation
          • Violated court-ordered parenting time (329+ days)
          • Engaged in documented parental alienation
          • Abused ex parte procedures through repeated false emergency claims
          • Violated MCL 722.27a duty to facilitate parenting time
          • Pattern of dishonesty spanning two years
          • Willingness to harm child's relationship with father to achieve litigation advantage

     The pattern of false allegations raises serious moral fitness concerns. A parent who is willing to lie to police, medical professionals, and courts—and to deprive a child of a relationship with the other parent based on those lies—has demonstrated a fundamental lack of moral fitness.

     "Moral fitness" includes honesty, integrity, and respect for legal and social norms. Defendant's conduct fails this standard.

7. Factor (g): Mental and Physical Health

     STRONGLY FAVORS PLAINTIFF

     PLAINTIFF:
          • HealthWest evaluation: No mental health issues, instability, or safety concerns
          • No history of mental health treatment
          • All allegations of suicidality, instability, and mental health concerns conclusively disproven
          • Medical records confirm absence of mental health diagnosis
          • Cleared by police investigations
          • Court awarded equal legal custody on July 17, 2024, implicitly finding Plaintiff mentally fit

     DEFENDANT:
          • No formal mental health concerns documented
          • However, pattern of false allegations and alienation behaviors raise questions about judgment and emotional regulation
          • Willingness to fabricate allegations of poisoning, assault, and threat suggests possible personality disorder traits (though no formal diagnosis in record)

     This factor strongly favors Plaintiff based on the HealthWest evaluation and complete absence of any legitimate mental health concerns.

8. Factor (h): Home, School, and Community Record

     EQUAL or FAVORS PLAINTIFF

     The child is of preschool age. Both parties maintain appropriate homes and community connections.

     Plaintiff has been actively involved in the child's developmental activities and medical care when permitted parenting time.

     To the extent the child has experienced disruption, it is directly attributable to Defendant's interference with the relationship with Plaintiff, not to any deficiency in Plaintiff's home or community involvement.

9. Factor (i): Reasonable Preference of Child

     NOT APPLICABLE

     The child is five years old and not of sufficient age to express a meaningful preference regarding custody. MCL 722.23(i).

     To the extent the child has expressed any reluctance to see Plaintiff, such reluctance is the direct result of Defendant's alienation tactics and should not be considered a "reasonable preference" but rather evidence of alienation.

10. Factor (j): Willingness to Facilitate Relationship

     EXTREMELY STRONGLY FAVORS PLAINTIFF

     This is the most critical factor in this case.

     PLAINTIFF:
          • Consistently sought to maintain relationship with child
          • Complied with all court orders
          • Pursued legal remedies appropriately (did not resort to self-help)
          • Completed HealthWest evaluation as requested
          • Demonstrated willingness to co-parent with Defendant
          • Has never interfered with Defendant's parenting time
          • Has never made false allegations against Defendant
          • Has never sought to eliminate Defendant from child's life

     DEFENDANT:
          • 329+ days of wrongful deprivation
          • Systematic false allegations designed to eliminate Plaintiff
          • Abuse of PPO process to interfere with parenting time
          • Abuse of ex parte emergency procedures (5+ orders)
          • Documented parental alienation (per HealthWest)
          • Violation of MCL 722.27a presumption
          • Complete unwillingness to facilitate relationship
          • Active campaign to destroy parent-child relationship

     Defendant has not merely failed to facilitate the relationship; she has actively and systematically worked to destroy it through:
          • False allegations to police
          • False allegations to medical providers
          • False allegations to courts
          • Fraudulent PPO
          • Strategic withholding
          • Alienation tactics

     Michigan case law recognizes that a parent's unwillingness to facilitate the relationship with the other parent is one of the most important factors in custody determinations. Foskett v Foskett, 247 Mich App 1 (2001); Simons v Gisvold, 236 Mich App 163 (1999).

     A parent who has deprived the child of 329+ days of contact with the other parent, through false allegations and abuse of legal process, has demonstrated an absolute unwillingness to facilitate the relationship.

     This factor alone justifies modification of custody.

11. Factor (k): Domestic Violence

     FAVORS PLAINTIFF

     There has been no domestic violence in this case.

     All of Defendant's allegations of threat, assault, and danger have been conclusively disproven by:
          • Police investigations (no charges filed)
          • Medical records (no injuries)
          • HealthWest evaluation (no concerns)
          • Court's own order awarding equal legal custody on July 17, 2024

     The fraudulent PPO was obtained through misrepresentation, not legitimate domestic violence.

     False allegations of domestic violence are themselves a form of abuse—abuse of the legal process, abuse of the other parent's reputation and rights, and abuse of the child's need for both parents.

     This factor favors Plaintiff both because: (1) there was no domestic violence by Plaintiff, and (2) Defendant's false allegations constitute abuse of process.

12. Factor (l): Any Other Relevant Factor

     FAVORS PLAINTIFF

     Additional relevant factors include:

     a. Professional Recommendation: The HealthWest evaluation recommends restoration and expansion of Plaintiff's parenting time, providing professional support for modification.

     b. Pattern of Contempt: Defendant's 329+ days of parenting time violations constitute criminal contempt under MCL 600.1715 and civil contempt under MCR 3.208, demonstrating a pattern of lawlessness.

     c. Fraud on the Court: Defendant's false allegations and fraudulent PPO constitute fraud on the court under MCR 2.612, warranting remedial action.

     d. Best Interests Presumption: MCL 722.27a establishes a statutory presumption that parenting time is in the child's best interests unless clear and convincing evidence shows it would endanger the child. No such evidence exists. All allegations have been disproven.

     e. Child's Developmental Needs: A five-year-old child needs both parents. Developmental psychology recognizes that father involvement is critical for healthy child development. The child has been deprived of this relationship for nearly a year.

     f. Harm from Continued Deprivation: Each additional day of deprivation causes further harm to the parent-child relationship and the child's psychological development. Immediate modification is necessary to prevent continued harm.

E. SUMMARY OF BEST INTERESTS ANALYSIS

     Applying the twelve statutory factors:

          • Factor (a): Favors Plaintiff or Equal
          • Factor (b): Favors Plaintiff
          • Factor (c): Equal or Favors Plaintiff
          • Factor (d): Favors Defendant (or Equal with modification)
          • Factor (e): Equal
          • Factor (f): Strongly Favors Plaintiff
          • Factor (g): Strongly Favors Plaintiff
          • Factor (h): Equal or Favors Plaintiff
          • Factor (i): Not Applicable
          • Factor (j): Extremely Strongly Favors Plaintiff
          • Factor (k): Favors Plaintiff
          • Factor (l): Favors Plaintiff

     RESULT: 9 of 12 factors favor Plaintiff (or 8 of 11 excluding not applicable factors)

     Only one factor (continuity) favors Defendant, and even that factor is compromised by the unlawful means through which the current arrangement was achieved.

     The overwhelming weight of the statutory best interest factors supports modification of custody to establish either:
          (1) Joint physical custody with equal parenting time (182.5 overnights each per year); or
          (2) Plaintiff as primary physical custodian with Defendant receiving parenting time.

F. THE JULY 17, 2024 ORDER SHOULD BE MODIFIED

     1. The July 17, 2024 order reduced Plaintiff's parenting time from 182.5 overnights per year to 79 overnights per year—a 56.7% reduction—without clear and convincing evidence of harm.

     2. That order was based in part on Defendant's false allegations, which have since been conclusively disproven by the HealthWest evaluation, medical records, and police reports.

     3. Since that order, Defendant has demonstrated such extreme unwillingness to facilitate any relationship between Plaintiff and the child that the factual predicate for that order (assumption that Defendant would comply with court-ordered parenting time) has been destroyed.

     4. The 329+ days of deprivation since that order demonstrate that the current custody arrangement is not working and is causing severe harm to the child.

     5. Modification is necessary to:
          • Restore the parent-child relationship
          • Protect the child from further alienation
          • Ensure compliance with MCL 722.27a
          • Hold Defendant accountable for violations
          • Prevent continued abuse of process

G. EQUAL PARENTING TIME IS IN THE CHILD'S BEST INTERESTS

     Plaintiff requests that the Court establish joint physical custody with equal parenting time (182.5 overnights each per year).

     This arrangement:
          • Restores the arrangement that existed before court involvement
          • Maximizes the child's time with both parents
          • Is consistent with MCL 722.27a's presumption favoring parenting time
          • Is supported by the HealthWest evaluation
          • Addresses the harm caused by 329+ days of deprivation
          • Is consistent with the best interests factors
          • Reflects the reality that both parents have appropriate capacity to parent

     Equal parenting time will:
          • Allow the child to maintain strong relationships with both parents
          • Reduce conflict by eliminating Defendant's control over access
          • Provide accountability (equal time leaves no room for gatekeeping)
          • Model healthy co-parenting for the child
          • Comply with Michigan's strong public policy favoring parenting time

H. ALTERNATIVELY, PLAINTIFF SHOULD BE PRIMARY CUSTODIAN

     If the Court declines to order equal parenting time, Plaintiff requests that he be designated the primary physical custodian with Defendant receiving reasonable parenting time.

     This alternative is justified by:

     1. Defendant's demonstrated unwillingness to comply with court orders (329+ days of violations)
     2. Defendant's pattern of false allegations and fraud on the court
     3. Defendant's moral fitness concerns (Factor (f))
     4. Defendant's extreme unwillingness to facilitate the relationship (Factor (j))
     5. The need for a custodial arrangement that Defendant cannot sabotage through false allegations and gatekeeping

     Designating Plaintiff as primary custodian would:
          • Protect the child from further alienation
          • Ensure compliance with parenting time orders (Plaintiff has never violated Defendant's time)
          • Remove Defendant's ability to weaponize custody
          • Hold Defendant accountable for violations
          • Provide the child with a stable environment with the parent who will facilitate the relationship with both parents

     Under this alternative, Defendant would receive reasonable parenting time, which Plaintiff commits to facilitating and encouraging.

I. MAKEUP PARENTING TIME MUST BE AWARDED

     Plaintiff has been wrongfully deprived of 329+ days of parenting time. This deprivation constitutes irreparable harm to both Plaintiff and the child.

     Michigan law requires that makeup parenting time be awarded when parenting time has been wrongfully denied. MCL 722.27a(3); MacIntyre v MacIntyre, 267 Mich App 449 (2005).

     Plaintiff requests:
          • 329 days of makeup parenting time to be scheduled at Plaintiff's discretion
          • Such time to be in addition to ongoing parenting time
          • Defendant to be ordered not to interfere with makeup time
          • Sanctions for any future violations

J. ATTORNEY FEES AND COSTS SHOULD BE AWARDED

     MCR 3.206(C) permits an award of attorney fees and costs based on:
          • The parties' financial circumstances
          • Whether the party acted in good faith
          • Whether the party had a reasonable basis for position
          • Whether fees were incurred solely for delay, harassment, or other improper purpose

     Plaintiff is entitled to attorney fees because:

     1. Defendant's conduct has necessitated this motion
     2. Defendant had no reasonable basis for 329+ days of parenting time deprivation
     3. Defendant's false allegations and abuse of process constitute bad faith
     4. Plaintiff has been forced to incur substantial attorney fees to vindicate his fundamental constitutional right to parent his child
     5. Defendant's violations were knowing and willful

     An award of attorney fees serves to:
          • Compensate Plaintiff for fees incurred due to Defendant's misconduct
          • Deter future violations
          • Hold Defendant accountable
          • Ensure access to justice

V. PROPOSED CUSTODY SCHEDULE

     Plaintiff proposes the following custody and parenting time schedule:

A. Legal Custody

     Joint legal custody to both parents (as currently ordered).

B. Physical Custody

     Joint physical custody with equal parenting time, or alternatively, Plaintiff as primary physical custodian.

C. Parenting Time Schedule (if joint physical custody ordered)

     Week 1: Monday-Tuesday-Wednesday with Father; Thursday-Friday-Saturday-Sunday with Mother
     Week 2: Thursday-Friday-Saturday-Sunday with Father; Monday-Tuesday-Wednesday with Mother

     This schedule provides each parent with 182.5 overnights per year (50% time).

     Alternatively, a 2-2-3 schedule or 2-2-5-5 schedule as the Court deems appropriate.

D. Parenting Time Schedule (if Father designated primary custodian)

     Father: Primary residence
     Mother: Alternating weekends (Friday 6pm to Sunday 6pm) plus one midweek overnight

E. Holiday and Summer Schedule

     To be determined by the Court or by agreement of the parties, consistent with equal division of holiday and vacation time.

F. Makeup Parenting Time

     329 days of makeup parenting time to be scheduled at Father's discretion, in blocks of no less than 3 consecutive days, to be completed within 18 months.

VI. CONCLUSION

     Plaintiff has demonstrated proper cause and change of circumstances by clear and convincing evidence. The systematic deprivation of 329+ days of parenting time, combined with Defendant's pattern of false allegations, parental alienation, and abuse of legal process, constitutes grounds for immediate modification of custody.

     Application of the twelve statutory best interest factors under MCL 722.23 overwhelmingly favors modification, with 9 of 12 factors favoring Plaintiff.

     The current custody arrangement has failed. Defendant has demonstrated an absolute unwillingness to facilitate the child's relationship with Plaintiff, in direct violation of MCL 722.27a and MCL 722.23(j).

     The child has a fundamental right to a relationship with both parents. That right has been violated for 329+ days. Further deprivation will cause irreparable harm.

     Modification of custody to establish joint physical custody with equal parenting time is necessary, appropriate, and in the child's best interests.

     WHEREFORE, Plaintiff respectfully requests that this Honorable Court:

     A. Grant this Motion to Modify Custody;
     B. Find that proper cause and/or change of circumstances exists;
     C. Find that an established custodial environment exists with both parents, or alternatively, only with Defendant;
     D. Conduct a best interests analysis under MCL 722.23;
     E. Find that 9 of 12 statutory best interest factors favor Plaintiff;
     F. Modify custody to establish joint physical custody with equal parenting time (182.5 overnights each per year);
     G. Alternatively, establish Plaintiff as primary physical custodian with Defendant receiving reasonable parenting time;
     H. Award 329 days of makeup parenting time to be scheduled at Plaintiff's discretion;
     I. Order Defendant to comply with MCL 722.27a and facilitate parenting time;
     J. Award attorney fees and costs to Plaintiff pursuant to MCR 3.206(C);
     K. Grant such other and further relief as the Court deems just and equitable.

